{"id":14881447,"mediaExerciseId":"3c7c24d1-7210-4f81-b7ae-c2a5063d8c0f","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"14","chapterTitle":"Cost of Capital","groupId":612387,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":487,"solutions":[{"id":5981483,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"First, lets begin with the $DCF$ model has the following advantages:\n\n$i)$ This model is extremely straightforward.\n\n$ii)$ This model is quite detailed.\n\n$iii)$ This aids in determining a company's intrinsic value.\n\n$iv)$ It is beneficial to the sensitivity analysis.\n\n\n.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":210,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/0ad4b19a60b4df3d0ca81e7ce53a5da8/edc3913e1b1aab72bcb8074fa35bdb30/lateximg_large.png","width":900},"regular":{"height":107,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/0ad4b19a60b4df3d0ca81e7ce53a5da8/edc3913e1b1aab72bcb8074fa35bdb30/lateximg.png","width":451}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Second, lets begin with the $DCF$ model has the following disadvantages:\n\n$i)$ Only when a corporation pays a dividend can this model be used.\n\n$ii)$ For this model to work, a constant growth rate is required.\n\n$iii)$ When valuing a company, the risk aspect of the business is not taken into account.\n\n$iv)$ This cost of equity is extremely sensitive to changes in the rate of growth","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/0ad4b19a60b4df3d0ca81e7ce53a5da8/84ae5823382edffb8dea495f6c33733f/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":111,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/04/0ad4b19a60b4df3d0ca81e7ce53a5da8/84ae5823382edffb8dea495f6c33733f/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"step